  "descriptions": [
    {
      "descrType": "Overview",
      "description": "The 48N6M is a long-range surface-to-air missile developed by Russia's Almaz-Antey, serving as the primary interceptor for both the S-300 (later variants) and S-400 air defense systems. Introduced in the early 1990s, the 48N6 family has become one of the most widely deployed Russian air defense missiles, capable of engaging aircraft, helicopters, and cruise missiles at ranges up to 250 kilometers. The missile employs semi-active radar guidance with track-via-missile mode, allowing the launch system to guide multiple missiles simultaneously against different targets.",
      "shortDescription": "Long-range semi-active radar guided SAM employed by S-300 and S-400 systems.",
      "classification": "U"
    },
    {
      "descrType": "Design",
      "description": "The 48N6M features a cylindrical body with delta control fins at the rear and mid-body configuration optimized for stability and range. Propulsion consists of a two-stage solid-fuel rocket motor enabling sustained cruise at transonic speeds and terminal phase acceleration. Guidance is primarily semi-active radar homing with track-via-missile capability, allowing the launch platform to illuminate the target while the missile provides guidance corrections via transmitted signals. The warhead is a high-explosive directed-fragmentation type tailored for aerial targets. Multiple variants (48N6, 48N6DM, 48N6E2) represent incremental improvements in range, guidance precision, and high-altitude engagement capability.",
      "shortDescription": "Two-stage SAM with semi-active radar guidance and multi-target engagement capability.",
      "classification": "U"
    }
  ],
